# Incentives Matter

???

- Because when we build things, we don't just finish them and move on.
- We have to maintain them.
- And without the right incentives, we'll inevitably drop the ball.
- Priorities are _always_ changing.
- Institutional memory doesn't actually last that long.
- And in this case, we had 3 teams with misaligned incentives.

---
class: center, middle

<img width="50%" src="data:image/png;base64," />

???

- We had the B4B Sales team, who desperately needed this product.
- We had the Retail team, who builds the thing that we need to be able to demo.
- And we had the B4B Engineering team, who were eager but ill-equipped to help, since Retail isn't their primary domain.
- So, to fix the demo environment, I needed to realign these incentives.

- And, again, since it was just _me_ on the project, I needed to be able to do it without building a ton of new things.

# Step 2: Stop Using Sanitized Data
## Solution: FactoryBot
### (some assembly required)

???

- Again, we have this great tool that we use to build fake users locally. Why not use it here?
- This is probably where I put in the most up-front work.
- Because, it turns out, that FactoryBot wasn't actually designed to run on anything other than an EMPTY database.
- It comes down to sequences:

---
class: middle

```ruby
sequence(:social_security_number) { |n| (999999999 - n).to_s.rjust(9, '0') }
```

???

- So, when factorybot boots up, sequences always start at 0
- But if we have data in our database, we have uniqueness constraints that will prevent duplicate entries
- So we need to start at the current MAX value plus one.
- But for encrypted values like a social security number, and nonstandard sequences in general, we can't just take the MAX

---
class: middle

# "CleverSequence"

```ruby
  LowerBoundFinder = Struct.new(:klass, :column_name, :block) do
    def lower_bound(current = 1, lower = 0, upper = Float::INFINITY)
      if exists?(current)
        lower_bound(next_between(current, upper), [current, lower].max, upper)
      elsif current - lower > 1
        lower_bound(next_between(lower, current), lower, [current, upper].min)
      else # current should == lower + 1
        lower
      end
    end

    private

    def next_between(lower, upper)
      [(lower + 1) / 2 + upper / 2, lower * 2].min
    end

    def exists?(value)
      klass.public_send(finder_method, block.call(value))
    end
  end
```

???

- So I monkey-patched the way FactoryBot sequences work...
- It uses an exponential search algorithm to query for the next in the sequence.
- So, if i is the next in the sequence, it will run in O(log(i)) time.
- It then _caches_ the value for the duration of that thread.
- I called it "CleverSequence"
- Because "clever" code isn't necessarily "good" code

# Step 6: It's maintained by _everyone_
## Solution: All Y'all

???

It's maintained by _everyone_.

Why? I didn't want to finish this project by saying, hey here's a new responsibility, you HAVE to take this on. Sorry.

Rather, when I stepped back and looked, what I saw was a tragedy of the commons.
It was _already_ a failure in collective ownership, with the burden saddled on just a few engineers and a desperate sales team.

- But, when you start to make it look a lot more like everything else we build,
- Relying on the same tools we use to build the features in the first place,
- And a continuously-deployed production instance with real SLAs and observability,
- And tests that step through common sales demos and fail builds if we break them,
- suddenly, everyone is maintaining it without even trying.

So when I say _everyone_ maintains it, I'm not saying everyone is _responsible_ for it.
But by doing what we do every day, we _all_ help _maintain_ the demo app.
